{{Infobox artwork | title = Silicon Forest | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | image = | image_size = | alt = | caption = | artist = [[Brian Borrello]] | catalogue = | year = {{start date|2003}} | completion_date = <!-- For a more specific date (post-1583): {{start date|YYYY|MM|DD|df=y}} --> | type = Sculpture | material = {{Flatlist| * Stainless steel * [[Light-emitting diode|LED]] lights }} | subject = Trees | height_metric = <!-- (i.e. in metric units) --> | width_metric = | length_metric = | diameter_metric = | height_imperial = <!-- (i.e. in imperial units) --> | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter_imperial = | dimensions = | dimensions_ref = | metric_unit = cm <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | imperial_unit = in <!-- Note: this parameter must either use the value given or not be included --> | condition = | city = [[Portland, Oregon]], United States | museum = | accession = | coordinates = {{coord|45.53005|-122.66769|display=inline,title}} | pushpin_map = Portland downtown | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Portland, Oregon | pushpin_label_position = | owner = | preceded_by = <!-- preceding work by the same artist --> | followed_by = <!-- next work by the same artist --> | website = <!-- Official webpage/site only: {{URL|example.com}} --> }} '''''Silicon Forest''''', sometimes referred to as '''''The Silicon Forest''''',<ref name=Solar>{{cite journal|last=Andorka|first=Frank|title=11 Must-See Art Installations, Inspired by Solar Panels: 3. The Silicon Forest, Portland, Ore.|journal=Solar Power World|date=May 7, 2013|url=http://www.solarpowerworldonline.com/2013/05/solar-panel-art-installations/3/|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> is an outdoor 2003 sculpture by [[Brian Borrello]], installed near the [[Interstate/Rose Quarter MAX Station]] in [[Portland, Oregon]]'s [[Lloyd District]], in the United States.
==Description and reception== Brian Borrello's ''Silicon Forest'' (2003) is an [[Abstract art|abstract]] sculpture made of stainless steel and [[light-emitting diode]] (LED) lights, installed at the [[Interstate/Rose Quarter MAX Station]] in Portland's [[Lloyd District]].<ref name=RACC>{{cite web|title=Public Art Walking Tour|url=http://racc.org/sites/default/files/NewPublicArtBrochure07.pdf|publisher=[[Regional Arts & Culture Council]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015|format=PDF|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006113837/http://racc.org/sites/default/files/NewPublicArtBrochure07.pdf|archivedate=October 6, 2014|df=}}</ref> It depicts a series of trees with thin trunks and cone-shaped foliage.<ref>{{cite web|title=Silicon Forest, (sculpture).|url=http://siris-artinventories.si.edu/ipac20/ipac.jsp?&profile=all&source=~!siartinventories&uri=full=3100001~!369005~!0#focus|publisher=[[Smithsonian Institution]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> The piece has been called a "three-part metaphor for displacement and change".<ref name=TriMet>{{Cite web|url=http://trimet.org/publicart/yellowlineart.htm|title=Public Art on MAX Yellow Line|publisher=[[TriMet]]|accessdate=November 6, 2015}}</ref> The solar artwork's steel trees illuminate using electricity powered by solar panels.<ref name=TriMet/>
In 2013, ''Solar Power World''{{'s}} Frank Andorka ranked the sculpture third in his list of "11 Must-See Art Installations, Inspired by Solar Panels".<ref name=Solar/>
