[[File:Englishmans Library frontispiece.jpg|thumb|Frontispiece found in vol. 10 of the Library]] {{italic title}} '''''The Englishman's Library''''' was an English book series of the 1840s, a venture of the publisher [[James Burns (publisher)|James Burns]]. It ran eventually to 31 volumes.
The title had been used already in 1824, for ''The Englishman's library'', edited by E. H. L., published by [[Charles Knight (publisher)|Charles Knight]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Englishman|title=The Englishman's Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OdgGAAAAQAAJ|accessdate=6 January 2013|year=1824}}</ref> The series was announced in ambitious fashion in the ''[[British Critic]]''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The British Critic, Quarterly Theological Review, and Ecclesiastical Record|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bUUDAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA250|accessdate=6 January 2013|year=1839|publisher=C. & J. Rivington, and J. Mawman|pages=250–1}}</ref> It was started by [[William Gresley (divine)|William Gresley]] and [[Edward Churton]], with propagandistic aims; the works are still a source for the "[[condition of England]]" debate of the time. Gresley wrote six novels for the series.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Sutherland|title=The Stanford Companion to Victorian Fiction|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=QzJ3yNVVqtUC&pg=PA264|accessdate=6 January 2013|date=1 November 1990|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-1842-4|page=264}}</ref>
==Aims== According to its prospectus, the Library aimed to "unite a popular style with sound Christian principles". The announced authors did not in fact all contribute.<ref>{{cite book|author=John Henry Newman|title=Letters and Diaries of John Henry Newman: Littlemore and the parting of friends May 1842-October 1843|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=d_SWAJPBo5wC&pg=PA300|accessdate=6 January 2013|year=1961|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-925458-3|page=300 note 3}}</ref>
Those behind the series were younger [[High Church]] men who wished to imitate some of the success of the ''[[Tracts for the Times]]''. They were less hostile to the Tractarians than older, more orthodox members of the [[Hackney Phalanx]].<ref>{{cite book|author1=Peter B. Nockles|author2=Peter Benedict Nockles|title=The Oxford Movement in Context: Anglican High Churchmanship, 1760-1857|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jM8Fk_iF1YMC&pg=PA286|accessdate=6 January 2013|year=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-58719-8|page=286}}</ref>
